SOP: DLP Policy Design & Rollout (Tool Agnostic)
Purpose
Create DLP policies deliberately (intent → detection → scope → actions → validation → enforcement) so policies act as guardrails instead of obstacles. 
Inputs
•	Risk scenario definition and “success looks like” statement 
•	Data definition (labels/patterns) + context constraints + risky actions 
•	Stakeholders and scope boundaries 
Process (Detailed)
1.	Intent Statement (1–2 sentences)
	The behavior you want to influence
	Which scenario(s) matter most
	What success metrics are (examples below as recommended template) 
2.	Detection Design
	Use a combination of: 
    	Content: sensitive info types / labeled content 
    	Context: location, destination, app/device, audience 
    	Action: share/copy/upload/paste/print/etc. 
	Prefer “clear and explainable” early detection; expand later (noise is harder to undo). 
3.	Scoping Rules (Start Narrow)
	Pilot group representative of different roles/departments 
	Limit initial locations to where risk truly occurs 
	Use inclusion/exclusion patterns to reduce noise (recommended template). 
4.	Action Strategy (Graduated Controls)
	Audit for baseline visibility 
	Warn to educate without interrupting work 
	Block with override when occasional legitimate business needs exist 
	Block when risk is clearly unacceptable 
5.	Simulation Validation 
	Run policy in simulation: conditions are evaluated and logged, not enforced 
	Review: 
      	Are the right types of data detected? 
      	Are legitimate activities flagged (false positives)? 
      	Is scope too broad/narrow? 
      	Are alerts meaningful or just noise? 
6.	Enforcement Readiness Criteria
	Triggers align with expected scenarios 
	False positives are limited and explainable 
	Users can understand why enforcement occurs (policy tips/notifications) 
7.	Deployment
	Phased rollout (pilot → expanded → full) 
	Monitor early enforcement impacts and overrides 
Outputs
•	Policy record: intent, scope, detection logic summary, action ladder, simulation results summary, enforcement date, owner. 
